{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"00e48010-4eab-4b41-8454-45e258f7a233","content":"Here's what you need:\n\n## Environment Variables\n\nFor NativeAOT on .NET 11, set these on your container:\n\n```yaml\nenv:\n  - name: DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump\n    value: \"1\"\n  - name: DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType\n    value: \"4\"            # 1=Mini, 2=Heap, 3=Triage, 4=Full\n  - name: DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpName\n    value: \"/dumps/core.%t.%p\"\n  - name: DOTNET_DbgCreatedumpPath\n    value: \"/opt/tools/createdump\"\n```\n\n## Pod Spec Changes\n\n```yaml\nspec:\n  containers:\n    - name: your-app\n      # ... existing config ...\n      securityContext:\n        capabilities:\n          add:\n            - SYS_PTRACE      # required for createdump to attach\n      volumeMounts:\n        - name: crash-dumps\n          mountPath: /dumps\n  volumes:\n    - name: crash-dumps\n      emptyDir:\n        sizeLimit: 2Gi       # adjust to your expected dump size\n```\n\n## Key points\n\n- **`SYS_PTRACE`** is mandatory — `createdump` uses `ptrace` to capture process memory.\n- **`%t.%p`** in the dump name expands to timestamp and PID, preventing overwrites.\n- **`DbgMiniDumpType=4`** gives full dumps; use `2` (Heap) if size is a concern.\n- The `emptyDir` volume is ephemeral — swap it for a PersistentVolumeClaim or push dumps to blob storage via a sidecar if you need them to survive pod restarts.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"3f59e5eb-f36d-4663-8f22-ac63a604e057","outputTokens":435,"requestId":"502D:2C454F:2500CA:2EB064:69F55494"},"id":"8c98e19f-a39b-4367-8cfb-5c026681e8d1","timestamp":"2026-05-02T01:34:22.936Z","parentId":"237d5e06-3ebc-4f4c-b44c-a263917b60df"}
